    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Missile Shield: A National Priority?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Barry Lobdell letter, commenting on Richard Perle's July 13 Op-Ed article, suggests that US share missile defense technology with all but the rogue states</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Senate Rejects Move for Tougher Testing of Antimissile System'' (news article, July 13):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Senate Rejects Move for Tougher Testing of Antimissile System'' (news article, July 13):</p>
        <p>There is nothing hostile in our plan for assembling and deploying a limited anti-missile defense system. So why not share the technology (if we ever get it to work) with fellow members of the nuclear club? Undoubtedly, the Russian and Chinese people would be happy to benefit from the same protection. And let's not forget France, Britain, India and Pakistan.  Once this expanded system is in place, no one should feel left out, except perhaps for those rogue states that will then have only each other for targets.</p>
        <p>BARRY LOBDELL  Saranac Lake, N.Y., July 13, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
